  "prompt": "Does a voltmeter show RMS voltage?",
  "response": "A standard voltmeter typically measures the root mean square (RMS) voltage of an alternating current (AC) signal if it is designed for AC measurements. This is because the RMS value is a standardized way to express the effective voltage of an AC signal, which can vary over time.\n\nHowever, it's important to note that not all voltmeters are the same. Some voltmeters may only measure direct current (DC) voltage or may not be true RMS (TRMS) meters. True RMS voltmeters are specifically designed to accurately measure the RMS voltage of varying waveforms, including non-sinusoidal waveforms. If you are using a voltmeter for AC measurements, make sure it is a true RMS voltmeter if you need accurate readings for complex waveforms.",
